  "doc_id": "52875",
  "text": "The evolving novel world of microRNA offers an additional regulatory layer affecting drug response. MicroRNAs (miRNAs) are a group of small non-coding, single-stranded RNAs of $22 nucleotides, that function as endogenous negative gene regulators by binding to the 3 0 -untranslated region (UTR) of target mRNAs, repressing mRNA translation or cleaving target mRNA [CITATION_1] . MiRNAs have been implicated in a wide array of fundamental biological processes, such as cell proliferation, differentiation, and apoptosis and thus may function as oncogenes or tumor suppressing genes. Accumulating evidence shows that miRNAs are grossly dysregulated in human cancers, including NSCLC.",
